sequenceDiagram
    participant User
    participant ClientA as Client A<br/>(Compromised/Phished)
    participant Attacker as Attacker<br/>(Actor in the Middle)
    participant IdP as Identity Provider<br/>(Legitimate)
    participant ClientB as Client B<br/>(Legitimate Target)

    Note over User,ClientB: IDP Session Token Theft & Reuse Attack

    %% Phase 1: User authenticates via compromised client
    Note over User,IdP: PHASE 1: Initial Authentication (Compromised Client)
    
    User->>ClientA: Visits compromised site<br/>(phishing or XSS-injected)
    ClientA->>IdP: Initiates OIDC flow<br/>GET /authorize?client_id=ClientA&redirect_uri=...
    
    IdP->>User: Redirect to IdP login page<br/>(user has no active IDP session)
    Note over IdP: IDP session does not exist yet
    
    User->>IdP: Enters credentials + MFA
    IdP->>IdP: Validates credentials<br/>Creates IDP session
    
    Note over IdP: IDP SESSION CREATED<br/>Session cookie: idp_session=abc123<br/>Domain: idp.example.com<br/>Valid for all clients using this IDP
    
    IdP->>User: Sets IDP session cookie<br/>Redirects with auth code to ClientA
    Note over User: Browser now has:<br/>Cookie: idp_session=abc123<br/>Domain: idp.example.com
    
    User->>ClientA: Delivers auth code
    ClientA->>IdP: Exchange code for tokens<br/>POST /token (code + client_secret)
    IdP->>ClientA: Returns access_token, id_token
    
    ClientA->>User: User logged into ClientA
    
    %% Phase 2: Attacker steals IDP session
    Note over User,Attacker: PHASE 2: IDP Session Token Theft
    
    Note over ClientA,Attacker: Attacker compromised ClientA with:<br/>• XSS vulnerability<br/>• Malicious script injection<br/>• Man-in-the-browser attack
    
    ClientA->>Attacker: Malicious script exfiltrates cookies
    Note over Attacker: Script cannot directly read<br/>HttpOnly cookies, but can:<br/>• Trigger requests to attacker domain<br/>• Capture cookies via network interception<br/>• Use browser extension malware
    
    User->>Attacker: Browser sends cookies to attacker-controlled endpoint
    Note over Attacker: ATTACKER CAPTURES:<br/>✓ IDP session cookie (idp_session=abc123)<br/>✓ Cookie is valid for idp.example.com<br/>✓ Cookie works for ANY client using this IDP
    
    %% Phase 3: Attacker uses stolen session on Client B
    Note over Attacker,ClientB: PHASE 3: Session Reuse on Different Client
    
    Attacker->>ClientB: Initiates login to Client B<br/>(legitimate service using same IDP)
    ClientB->>IdP: OIDC auth request<br/>GET /authorize?client_id=ClientB&redirect_uri=...
    
    Note over Attacker: Attacker injects stolen IDP session cookie<br/>Cookie: idp_session=abc123
    
    Attacker->>IdP: Request includes stolen session cookie
    
    IdP->>IdP: Validates session cookie<br/>Session is valid!<br/>User already authenticated
    
    Note over IdP: IDP sees valid session<br/>No re-authentication needed<br/>Assumes this is the legitimate user
    
    IdP->>Attacker: Auto-approves authorization<br/>Redirects with auth code for ClientB<br/>(NO credential prompt!)
    
    Attacker->>ClientB: Delivers auth code
    ClientB->>IdP: Exchange code for tokens<br/>POST /token (code + client_secret)
    IdP->>ClientB: Returns access_token, id_token<br/>for the victim user
    
    ClientB->>Attacker: Attacker logged in as victim user
    
    Note over Attacker: ATTACK SUCCESSFUL<br/>✓ Logged into Client B as victim<br/>✓ No credentials needed<br/>✓ No MFA challenge<br/>✓ Bypassed all authentication
    
    %% Summary
    Note over User,ClientB: KEY POINTS:<br/><br/>ATTACK SUCCESS FACTORS:<br/>• IDP session cookie is domain-scoped (idp.example.com)<br/>• Single IDP session works across ALL clients<br/>• IDP doesn't re-authenticate if valid session exists<br/>• Session cookies often long-lived (hours/days)<br/><br/>MITIGATION STRATEGIES:<br/>• Short IDP session timeouts<br/>• HttpOnly + Secure + SameSite=Strict cookies<br/>• IDP device/IP binding<br/>• Step-up authentication for sensitive clients<br/>• Continuous authentication monitoring<br/>• Client-specific consent prompts

